
What is a Map?

A Map is a collection of key-value pairs, similar to objects—but more powerful and flexible.

const map = new Map();

map.set("name", "John");
map.set(1, "Number key");

console.log(map.get("name")); // John
Key Features of Map
Keys can be any data type (string, number, object, etc.)
Maintains insertion order
Has built-in methods like .set(), .get(), .has()


Map
 ┌───────────────┐
 │ "name" → John │
 │ 1      → Num  │
 │ {}     → Obj  │
 └───────────────┘

What is a Set?

A Set is a collection of unique *values* only.
const set = new Set();

set.add(1);
set.add(2);
set.add(2); // duplicate

console.log(set); // {1, 2}

Key Features of Set
Stores only unique values
Automatically removes duplicates
Maintains insertion order
Set
 ┌─────────┐
 │ 1       │
 │ 2       │
 │ 3       │
 └─────────┘
(No duplicates allowed)


-- Problems with Traditional Objects and Arrays
Objects (Problems)
const obj = {};
obj[true] = "yes";
obj["true"] = "no";

console.log(obj); // { true: "no" }

❌ Keys are converted to strings
❌ No guaranteed order (historically)
❌ No easy size checking - no inbuilt length property.

Arrays (Problems)
const arr = [1, 2, 2, 3];

❌ Allows duplicates
❌ Harder to check uniqueness efficiently


-- MAP VS OBJECT
| Feature   | Map               | Object                  |
| --------- | ----------------- | ----------------------- |
| Key types | Any type          | Strings/Symbols only    |
| Order     | Maintained        | Not reliable (older JS) |
| Size      | `.size`           | `Object.keys().length`  |
| Iteration | Easy (`for...of`) | Less direct             |

Example
// Map
const map = new Map();
map.set({}, "value");

// Object
const obj = {};
obj[{}] = "value";

console.log(obj); // [object Object
👉 Object loses uniqueness of object keys
👉 Map keeps them distinct ✅

--Set vs Array

| Feature      | Set            | Array               |
| ------------ | -------------- | ------------------- |
| Duplicates   | ❌ Not allowed  | ✅ Allowed           |
| Lookup speed | Faster (`has`) | Slower (`includes`) |
| Order        | Maintained     | Maintained          |
| Use case     | Unique values  | Indexed data        |

const arr = [1, 2, 2, 3];

const unique = new Set(arr);

console.log(unique); // {1, 2, 3}
👉 Super easy way to remove duplicates!

---When to Use Map and Set
Use Map when:
You need key-value storage
Keys are not just strings
You need frequent additions/removals

const userRoles = new Map();
userRoles.set(userObject, "admin");
-

Use Set when:
You need unique values only
You want to remove duplicates
You need fast existence checks
const visitedPages = new Set();
visitedPages.add("/home");

